**HOA Document Management System**

Comprehensive Feature Specification

Prepared for: Talasera HOA Platform Project

Version 1.0 \| March 2026

*DELIVERABLES: Document Taxonomy • Access Control Matrix • Workflow
Diagrams • Template Requirements • Technical Architecture • Feature
Specification*

Table of Contents

1\. Executive Summary

This specification defines a comprehensive document management system
(DMS) for an HOA management SaaS platform. The system is designed to
serve self-managed and professionally managed homeowners associations,
starting with Talasera HOA (Washington State) and scaling to any
subscribing HOA nationwide.

The DMS addresses critical gaps identified in existing
platforms---particularly PayHOA, which lacks document versioning,
e-signatures, compliance tracking, retention automation, and template
sophistication. No platform in the self-managed HOA tier currently
provides true compliance-grade document management with version control,
audit trails, automated retention, or regulatory calendars.

This specification covers six deliverables: (1) a complete document
taxonomy covering 70+ document types across 12 categories, (2) an access
control matrix mapping every document type to the platform\'s 9-role
RBAC model, (3) document workflow diagrams for core operations, (4) a
template requirements list with merge field specifications, (5)
technical architecture recommendations with specific technology choices,
and (6) a feature specification covering search, versioning, sharing,
and compliance.

The architecture is designed for multi-state compliance, with Washington
State (RCW 64.38 and WUCIOA/RCW 64.90) as the initial implementation and
configurable compliance engines for all 50 states.

2\. Document Taxonomy

The following taxonomy identifies every document type an HOA needs to
manage, organized into 12 categories. For each document type, the table
specifies who creates it, the retention requirement (drawn from
Washington State statute and IRS requirements as the baseline, with
multi-state configurability), versioning needs, e-signature
applicability, and common file formats.

2.1 Governing Documents

Governing documents are the foundational legal instruments of an HOA.
They are permanent records under both Washington State law (RCW
64.38.045(4)(d)) and general best practice. These documents are amended
infrequently but require meticulous version control when changes occur.

