4\. Document Workflow Diagrams

The following workflow specifications describe the key document-centric
processes in the system. Each workflow identifies actors, trigger
conditions, process steps, decision points, and system behaviors. These
are designed to be implemented as configurable state machines with
event-driven transitions.

4.1 Document Upload and Processing Pipeline

This is the universal workflow triggered whenever any document enters
the system, whether uploaded manually, generated by the platform,
received via email, or ingested via API.

**Step 1 --- Ingest:** User uploads file or system generates document.
System captures: uploader identity, timestamp, source
(manual/system/email/API), associated entity (property, violation, ARC
case, etc.).

**Step 2 --- Virus Scan:** File passes through ClamAV or equivalent
malware scanner. Quarantine if flagged; notify admin. Block file from
entering document store until cleared.

**Step 3 --- Format Validation:** Verify file type against allowlist
(PDF, DOCX, XLSX, JPG, PNG, TIFF, MP4, CSV, DWG). Reject unsupported
formats with user-friendly error. Enforce file size limits (100MB
default, configurable per tenant).

**Step 4 --- Metadata Extraction:** Auto-extract metadata: file size,
page count, creation date, author (from file metadata). AI-assisted
classification: suggest document type, category, and tags based on
content analysis.

**Step 5 --- OCR Processing:** For scanned PDFs and images: queue for
asynchronous OCR via Amazon Textract. Extract text layer, store as
searchable PDF. Calculate and store OCR confidence score. Flag
low-confidence pages for human review.

**Step 6 --- Search Indexing:** Push document metadata, extracted text,
and OCR output to OpenSearch/Elasticsearch index. Index at page level
with document-level backreferences. Apply field boosts: title (3x),
headings (2x), body text (1x), tags (0.8x).

**Step 7 --- Storage:** Store original file in S3 with server-side
encryption (AES-256). Generate thumbnail/preview renditions. Apply
retention policy based on document type classification. Record in audit
log: document_id, uploader, timestamp, classification, retention_policy.

**Step 8 --- Notification:** If document is associated with a workflow
(e.g., ARC application, violation case), notify relevant parties. If
document requires review/approval, create task and assign to appropriate
role.

4.2 Records Request Fulfillment Workflow

This workflow implements compliance with Washington State\'s 10-day
acknowledgment / 21-day production requirement (WUCIOA) and is
configurable for all state response deadlines.

**Step 1 --- Request Intake:** Owner submits records request via portal,
email, or paper (scanned). System captures: requester identity, date
received, specific documents/categories requested. Clock starts
immediately.

**Step 2 --- Auto-Acknowledge:** System sends acknowledgment within 24
hours (well within 10-business-day requirement). Acknowledgment
includes: request reference number, estimated completion date,
applicable fees.

**Step 3 --- Document Assembly:** Manager receives task with deadline
countdown. System auto-suggests documents matching the request. Manager
reviews, adds/removes documents from fulfillment package.

**Step 4 --- Exemption Review:** System flags potentially exempt
documents: attorney-client privileged, personnel records, pending
litigation, individual enforcement records (identifying other owners),
individual account records. Manager confirms exemptions; system logs
reasoning.

**Step 5 --- Redaction:** For documents containing Address
Confidentiality Program participants: auto-redact addresses. For
documents with PII of non-requesting owners: manual or AI-assisted
redaction. Generate redacted versions; preserve originals.

**Step 6 --- Fee Calculation:** Calculate copy fees per state-specific
formula. Washington: reasonable fee (board-set policy). Arizona:
\$0.15/page max. California: direct and actual cost. System applies one
free annual owner list per RCW 64.38.045(8)(b).

**Step 7 --- Delivery:** Deliver via secure download link (preferred) or
physical mail. Track delivery confirmation. Record: documents provided,
documents withheld with reasons, fees charged, delivery method, delivery
date.

**Step 8 --- Deadline Monitoring:** System monitors approaching
deadlines with escalating alerts: 50% of time elapsed (yellow), 75%
(orange), 90% (red), deadline passed (critical + notification to board
president). Track penalty exposure per state (e.g., Florida \$50/day,
California \$500/violation, Nevada \$25/day).

4.3 Governing Document Amendment Workflow

**Step 1 --- Draft:** Board or attorney creates draft amendment. System
creates new version branch from current governing document. Track all
changes with full diff capability.

**Step 2 --- Board Review:** Distribute draft to all board members.
Collect comments and suggested changes via in-document collaboration or
discussion thread. Board votes to approve sending to membership.

**Step 3 --- Member Notice:** Generate and distribute notice of proposed
amendment per statutory requirements. Include full text of proposed
changes (required by WA statute). Track delivery via multi-channel
distribution.

**Step 4 --- Vote:** Conduct vote per governing document amendment
requirements (typically 67% of total membership). System manages ballot
distribution, collection, verification, and counting.

**Step 5 --- Recording:** If approved, prepare amendment for recording
with county recorder. Generate clean version incorporating all
amendments. E-signature collection for required signatories.

**Step 6 --- Publication:** Publish updated governing document to owner
portal. Notify all members of effective date. Archive prior version with
clear superseded marking. Update version history timeline.

4.4 Document Version Control Workflow

**Step 1 --- Check-Out:** User requests edit access to a versioned
document. System creates lock preventing concurrent edits. Lock is
time-bounded (configurable, default 4 hours) with automatic release and
notification.

**Step 2 --- Edit:** User modifies document (in-platform editor or
download/re-upload). System tracks: editor identity, timestamp, change
description (required field).

**Step 3 --- Check-In:** User saves new version. System stores complete
version (not deltas---storage is cheap, reliability is paramount).
Auto-generates diff between new and previous version. Increments version
number per semantic scheme: major.minor (e.g., CC&Rs v3.0 → v3.1 for
minor edit, v4.0 for formal amendment).

**Step 4 --- Review (if required):** For documents requiring approval
(governing docs, financial reports, minutes): route to approver(s).
Approval workflow configurable per document type. Rejected versions
remain in history but are marked as rejected.

**Step 5 --- Publish:** Approved version becomes the current active
version. Prior version moves to version history with clear status
labels: Current, Approved, Draft, Superseded, Rejected.

**Audit Trail:** Every version stores: version number, timestamp,
editor, approver (if applicable), change description, full document
content, diff from previous version. Audit trail is immutable and
tamper-evident.

4.5 Document Sharing and Distribution Workflow

**Bulk Distribution:** Select documents → Choose recipients (by role,
tag, property group, individual) → Choose delivery method (email
attachment, secure link, portal notification, physical mail via Lob) →
Track delivery status per recipient → Record in audit log.

**Secure External Sharing:** Generate time-limited, password-protected
download link → Send to external party (attorney, vendor, auditor) →
Track access (views, downloads) → Auto-expire link after configurable
period (default 30 days) → Revocable at any time.

**E-Signature Flow:** Select template or document → Populate merge
fields → Define signing order and required signatories → Send via
e-signature provider (DocuSeal recommended for self-hosted; Dropbox
Sign/DocuSign for managed) → Track signing status → Store completed
signed document with certificate of completion → File in appropriate
document category.

**Annual Meeting Packet Assembly:** System auto-compiles: meeting
notice, agenda, financial statements, budget, reserve study summary,
board candidate statements, proposed amendments, proxy form → Review by
board → Distribute per notice requirements → Track delivery.

